<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<handout>
<title>Daily Prep 4.2 - Matrix Algebra</title>

<section>
    <title>Overview</title>

  <p> 
This section introduces matrix algebra by beginning with the simplest case:
    1×1 matrices, which behave just like real numbers under addition, scalar
    multiplication, and composition. From this starting point, we see how
    these familiar operations naturally generalize to larger matrices.
  </p>

<p>
    We emphasize that matrices represent linear mappings between vector
    spaces, and that matrix operations—such as addition, scalar multiplication,
    and composition (matrix multiplication)—are defined so that they behave
    consistently with the way linear mappings act on vectors. 
  </p>


<p>
    We learn how to add matrices element‑wise, how scalar multiplication 
    applies uniformly to every entry, and how matrix multiplication corresponds 
    to composing linear transformations. Throughout, concrete numerical examples 
    illustrate how these algebraic rules connect to the action of matrices on 
    vectors and why mismatched matrix sizes make certain operations undefined.
  </p>

</section>

<section>
  <title>Basic learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          These are the tasks you should be able to perform with reasonable
          fluency when you arrive at our next class meeting.
          Important new
          vocabulary words are indicated <em>in italics</em>.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>

Understand that matrices represent linear mappings and that 1×1 matrices
      behave like real numbers.
            </p>
          </li>

<li>
<p>
Perform <em>matrix addition</em> and <em>scalar multiplication</em> when matrix sizes match.
</p>
</li>

          <li>
            <p>

Recognize when matrix operations are undefined due to incompatible
      dimensions.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

</section>

<section xml:id="sec-Toprepareforclass42">
  <title>Learn!</title>

  <p>
    Complete the actions listed below.
  </p>
  <ul>

<li>
  <p>
    <alert>Read</alert> <url href="
https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/matalg_section.html#matalg_section">Section A.2: Matrix algebra </url>.   
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
    (Optional) <alert>Do</alert> interact with the applet <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/m/nrshpujr">Matrix Addition and Scalar Multiplication</url> by Heather Pierce for practice.  
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
    (Optional) <alert>Do</alert> interact with the applet <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/m/KRwSUtRw">Multiplying Two Matrices</url> by Mathiyalagan.  
  </p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
(Optional) <alert>Watch</alert> <url href=" 
https://youtu.be/XkY2DOUCWMU?si=XvNtlt6gUL07kYs5">
Matrix Multiplication as Composition (10:03)</url> by 3Blue1Brown.
</p>
</li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Do</alert> <url href=" 
https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/matalg_section.html#subsection-175">Subsection A.2.8: Exercises 
A.2.2, A.2.3, A.2.4, A.2.5, A.2.103, A.2.105</url>.
          </p>
        </li>


        <li>
          <p>
            Try these additional questions.  If necessary, use AI to guide your thinking. 
          </p>
            <ol>

<li>
<p>
What is the relationship between dot product and matrix multiplication? 
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
What is the relationship between the product of a matrix <m>A</m> and a column vector and the product of matrix <m>A</m> with another matrix <m>B</m>?
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
Are all <em>nonzero</em> matrices invertible?  If not, can you give an example? 
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
Define <m>\displaystyle{A}= \left[ \begin{array}{cc}4 &#x26; -2 \\ 3 &#x26; -5 \\ 0 &#x26; 1\end{array} \right]</m> and <m>\displaystyle{B}= \left[ \begin{array}{cc}-4 &#x26; 2 \\ -24 &#x26; 26 \\ 6 &#x26; -7\end{array} \right]</m>.
Compute <m>3{A}</m> and <m>{A}+{B}</m>.
</p>
</li>

<li>
<p>
Compute <m>AB</m> where <m>\displaystyle A = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}4 &#x26; -2 \\ 3 &#x26; -5 \\ 0 &#x26; 1\end{array}\right]</m> and <m>\displaystyle B = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}2 &#x26; -3 \\ 6 &#x26; -7\end{array} \right]</m>.
</p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
If <m>A</m> is <m>4 \times 3</m> and <m>B</m> is <m>3 \times 2</m>, then what are the sizes of <m>AB</m> and <m>BA</m>?
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
Suppose <m>\displaystyle A = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}2 &#x26; 3 &#x26; 6 \\ -1 &#x26; 0 &#x26; 1\end{array} \right]</m> and <m>\displaystyle B = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}2 &#x26; -3 \\ 0 &#x26; 1 \\ 4 &#x26; -7\end{array} \right]</m>.
Compute <m>AB</m>.
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
Use <m>\displaystyle A = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}1 &#x26; 2 &#x26; 3 \\ 4 &#x26; 5 &#x26; 6\end{array} \right]</m> and <m>\displaystyle B = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}1 &#x26; 0 \\ 1 &#x26; 0 \\ -1 &#x26; -1\end{array} \right]</m> to demonstrate that <m>AB \neq BA</m> can happen.
  </p>
</li>

<li>
  <p>
Let <m>\displaystyle A = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc}1 &#x26; 2 &#x26; 0 \\ 3 &#x26; 0 &#x26; 1\end{array} \right]</m> and <m>B = \left[ \begin{array}{cc}1 &#x26; 2 \\ 0 &#x26; 1 \\ -2 &#x26; 4\end{array} \right]</m>.
Compute <m>AB</m>, <m>(AB)^{T}</m>, <m>A^{T}B^{T}</m>, and <m>B^{T}A^{T}</m>.
  </p>
</li>

</ol>
</li>


<li>
  <p>
    <alert>Do</alert> MyOpenMath questions from this section. 
  </p>
</li>


        
</ul>

<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-1">
  <title>Matrix Addition</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Matrices of the same size can be added entry‑wise.  
      Compute
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 3\\2 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}
        +
        \begin{bmatrix}4 \amp -1\\1 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \amp 2\\3 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — addition is performed entry‑wise.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 2\\1 \amp 5\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — the (1,1) and (2,1) entries are incorrect.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp 3\\2 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this is just the second matrix replaced incorrectly.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-2">
  <title>Scalar Multiplication</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Compute
      <m>
        3\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1\\4 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}6 \amp -3\\12 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — scalar multiplication multiplies each entry by the scalar.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}5 \amp -2\\7 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — each entry must be multiplied by 3.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\begin{bmatrix}6 \amp -1\\4 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — only some entries were scaled.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-3">
  <title>Matrix Multiplication (2×2)</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Matrix multiplication is <em>not</em> entry‑wise but uses row‑by‑column combinations.  
      Compute
      <me>
        \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 2\\3 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}
        \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 0\\1 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}.
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}4 \amp 8\\7 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          Row 1 · Col 1: 1·2 + 2·1 = 4.  
          Row 1 · Col 2: 1·0 + 2·4 = 8.  
          Row 2 · Col 1: 3·2 + 1·1 = 7.  
          Row 2 · Col 2: 3·0 + 1·4 = 4.  
          This follows the matrix‑product rule.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 8\\3 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — the (1,1) and (2,1) entries are wrong.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p><m>\begin{bmatrix}3 \amp 6\\5 \amp 4\end{bmatrix}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this incorrectly mixes entry‑wise multiplication.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-4">
  <title>Identity Matrix</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The identity matrix <m>I</m> is the matrix that leaves any vector unchanged.  
      Which of the following is the 3×3 identity matrix?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct.  
          The identity matrix has 1s on the diagonal and 0s elsewhere.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1\\
            1 \amp 1 \amp 1
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — that matrix does not act as an identity.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>
            \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            1 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0
            \end{bmatrix}
          </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback><p>No — this is not the identity matrix.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="matalg-mcq-5">
  <title>When Is Matrix Multiplication Defined?</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The product <m>AB</m> is defined only when:
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>The number of columns of <m>A</m> equals the number of rows of <m>B</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct — matrix multiplication requires the inner dimensions to match.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>A</m> and <m>B</m> must be square matrices.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — multiplication does not require square matrices.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The number of rows of <m>A</m> must equal the number of rows of <m>B</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No — rows do not determine the rule.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives42">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
Explain conceptually how matrix multiplication corresponds to composition
      of linear mappings.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p> 
Analyze examples illustrating how matrix operations affect the resulting
      action on vectors, using algebraic structure to justify results rather
      than computation alone.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
Relate familiar 1×1 mappings to higher‑dimensional cases and generalize
      the underlying algebraic principles to arbitrary matrix sizes.

            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>